					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/salvador-5" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1299715); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1299715&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164149" alt="Salvador 5" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1299715)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/salvador-5" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1299715); return false;" >Salvador 5</a></span> <span class="odate time_1544340099 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Dec 2018 07:21</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4080637">
									

<p>I really <em>want</em> to like this. I respect Kaktus and everything he's written on here. I'm just burned out on all of the grimdark. The concept is interesting. I just can't get myself to be interested in it.</p>
<p>It feels like the early-mid 90s when the opposite was happening - no one was doing dark endings very often, and while comics were actually coming <em>out</em> of that period, the &quot;happy ending&quot; felt overdone and tiresome. Except that at some point, <em>everyone</em> started doing grimdark as a reaction to that time, and no one got the message that it's tired, now. Just like with happy endings back then.</p>
<p>So, it's not a critique on the writing at all. God knows that Kaktus has proven himself more than capable time and time over. It just feels like the same theme done differently.</p>

							</div>

								
					
